Then $\angle ADE = \angle BDE = \angle CDE = 90^\circ,$ so $ADBE$ and $CDE$ are cyclic.  Hence,
\[\angle ACB = \angle ACD + \angle BCD = \angle AED + \angle BEC.\]By the Law of Sines on triangles $ADE$ and $BDE,$
\[\frac{AD}{\sin \angle AED} = \frac{DE}{\sin \angle ADE} = \frac{BD}{\sin \angle BDE}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{AD}{BD} = \frac{\sin \angle AED}{\sin \angle BDE}.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ADE,$
\[\cos \angle AED = \frac{AD^2 + DE^2 - AE^2}{2 \cdot AD \cdot DE} = \frac{AD^2 - AE^2}{AD \cdot DE}.\]Similarly,
\[\cos \angle BDE = \frac{BD^2 - BE^2}{BD \cdot DE}.\]Then
\[\cos \angle ACB = \cos (\angle AED + \angle BDE) = \cos \angle AED \cos \angle BDE - \sin \angle AED \sin \angle BDE.\]Hence,
\[\cos \angle ACB = \frac{AD^2 - AE^2}{AD \cdot DE} \cdot \frac{BD^2 - BE^2}{BD \cdot DE} - \frac{AD}{DE} \cdot \frac{BD}{DE} \cdot \sin \angle CAD \sin \angle CBD.\]We can compute $AD^2 - AE^2$ and $BD^2 - BE^2$ as follows:
\begin{align*}
AD^2 - AE^2 &= (AD + AE)(AD - AE) \\
&= (CD + CE)(AD - AE) \\
&= CD \cdot AD - CE \cdot AE, \\
BD^2 - BE^2 &= (BD + BE)(BD - BE) \\
&= (CD + CE)(BD - BE) \\
&= CD \cdot BD + CE \cdot BE.
\end{align*}Hence,
\begin{align*}
\cos \angle ACB &= \frac{(CD \cdot AD - CE \cdot AE)(CD \cdot BD + CE \cdot BE)}{AD \cdot BD \cdot DE^2} - \frac{CD \cdot BD}{DE^2} \cdot xy \\
&= \frac{CD}{DE^2} \cdot (AD \cdot BD - AE \cdot BE) - xy \\
&= \frac{CD}{DE^2} \cdot (AB^2 - AE \cdot BE) - xy.
\end{align*}By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABE,$
\[AB^2 = AE^2 + BE^2 - 2 \cdot AE \cdot BE \cos \angle ACB.\]Hence,
\[\cos \angle ACB = \frac{AB^2 - AE \cdot BE}{2 \cdot AE \cdot BE} + xy = \boxed{\frac{x^2 + y^2 - 1}{2xy}}.\]

