Let $x = CD$ and $y = CE.$  Then $AD = 2x$ and $BE = 2y.$  By the Law of Cosines on triangle $CDE,$
\[DE^2 = x^2 + y^2 - 2xy \cos 60^\circ = x^2 + y^2 - xy.\]By Pythagoras on triangles $ACD$ and $BCE,$
\begin{align*}
AC^2 &= 4x^2 + y^2, \\
BC^2 &= x^2 + 4y^2.
\end{align*}Then by the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\begin{align*}
AB^2 &= AC^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot AC \cdot BC \cdot \cos B \\
&= 4x^2 + y^2 + x^2 + 4y^2 - 2 \cdot (2xy) \cos B \\
&= 5x^2 + 5y^2 - 4xy \cos B.
\end{align*}Also, $AB^2 = AD^2 + DE^2 + EB^2,$ so
\[5x^2 + 5y^2 - 4xy \cos B = 4x^2 + 4y^2 + DE^2 + 4y^2.\]Hence,
\[DE^2 = x^2 + y^2 - xy = 5x^2 + y^2 - 4y^2 - 4x^2.\]Then $DE^2 = 4x^2 - 3y^2,$ so
\[\frac{DE^2}{BE^2} = \frac{8^2}{15^2}.\]Then
\[\frac{4x^2 - 3y^2}{4y^2} = \frac{64}{225}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{x^2}{y^2} - \frac{3}{4} = \frac{64}{225} \cdot \frac{1}{4} = \frac{16}{225}.\]Then $\frac{x^2}{y^2} = \frac{67}{225}.$

